2026-04-16 12:13:34 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 6 input cable negative terminal / internal 0V pass-through'] hypothesis_explanation='The visual inspection of the external cabling reported that all module‑to‑module connections are straight‑through with correct polarity, and no polarity inversions or other cable swaps were found anywhere in the chain. The single reported anomaly is that the n (0 V/return) terminal of Control Input Cable (+) 6 is disconnected (floating).\n\nIn this series system, both the +12 V and 0 V conductors must pass through every control module to reach the load. If the 0 V line is open at Control Module 6, then the return path from the load back to the battery is broken for all downstream modules (CM6, CM7, CM8, and the load module). This would prevent any substantial current from flowing to the lamp or to the module indicator circuits, even though the power‑supply LED is lit and all switches are closed. That matches the observed symptoms: supply LED on, all control‑module LEDs non‑functional, and the load lamp off.\n\nGiven that no other defects or polarity errors have been observed or measured, the simplest consistent root cause is an open 0 V connection at the negative terminal associated with Control Module 6’s input cable (either a faulty cable, loose connector, or broken internal 0 V pass‑through at that module). Repairing/replacing that connection should restore the 0 V continuity and allow the lamp and indicators to operate when switches are on.'
