2026-04-16 12:14:15 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Lamp in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU LED is on, so the battery and PSU module work. All eight control modules are reported with their switches closed and with no observable internal faults on visual inspection. External cabling has been verified: polarity is consistent end‑to‑end, with no conductor swaps and no visibly loose or missing terminals, including around CM6–CM8 and the load. Thus, a continuous 12 V and 0 V path should reach the load module when all switches are ON.\n\nGiven that the load module includes a series diode followed by two lamps in parallel (main lamp plus internal indicator), and that there is no evidence for a polarity error (which is what that diode primarily protects against), the most probable remaining single‑point failure that explains ‘lamp does not turn on’ is a fault in the lamp element itself (open filament/LED or internal connection), rather than in the wiring or upstream modules. If the main lamp is open, neither it nor the parallel indicator would illuminate under normal 12 V supply, even though the upstream chain is healthy.\n\nTherefore the root cause is most likely a failed lamp inside the load module. Replacing/repairing the lamp assembly in the load module should restore correct operation, assuming the upstream modules remain as inspected.'
